03944nam a22006735i 9780822372189DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20182018ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017022894  a97808223721897 a10.1515/97808223721892doi  a(DE-B1597)553674  a(OCoLC)1055359375  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aRC553.A88bY474 2018 7aSOC0120002bisacsh04a616.85882223/swe1 aYergeau, M. Remi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAuthoring Autism :bOn Rhetoric and Neurological Queerness /cM. Remi Yergeau. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b9 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThought in the Act : 1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Involution -- tOne. intention -- tTwo. Intervention -- tThree. Invitation -- tFour. Invention -- tEpilogue. Indexicality -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Authoring Autism Melanie Yergeau defines neurodivergence as an identity—neuroqueerness—rather than an impairment. Using a queer theory framework, Yergeau notes the stereotypes that deny autistic people their humanity and the chance to define themselves while also challenging cognitive studies scholarship and its reification of the neurological passivity of autistics. She also critiques early intensive behavioral interventions—which have much in common with gay conversion therapy—and questions the ableist privileging of intentionality and diplomacy in rhetorical traditions. Using storying as her method, she presents an alternative view of autistic rhetoricity by foregrounding the cunning rhetorical abilities of autistics and by framing autism as a narrative condition wherein autistics are the best-equipped people to define their experience. Contending that autism represents a queer way of being that simultaneously embraces and rejects the rhetorical, Yergeau shows how autistic people queer the lines of rhetoric, humanity, and agency. In so doing, she demonstrates how an autistic rhetoric requires the reconceptualization of rhetoric’s very essence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aAutism. 0aAutistic people. 0aDisability studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh  aCCCC Book Award Winners.  aLavender Rhetorics Book Award.  aMLA Book Awards.  aMLA First Book Prize Winner.  aNCTE Award Winners.  aRhetoric Society of America book awards.  adisability activism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106963320 cprintz978082237011640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822372189?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372189423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372189/original  a978-3-11-069633-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles